assify itself as “a street gang with analysis.” American activist Abbie Hoffman described the group as “the middle-class nightmare . . . an anti-media phenomenon simply because their name could not be printed.” Up Against the Real examines how and why the group ultimately rejected art in favor of what its members deemed “real” political action. Exploring this notorious example of cultural activism that rose from the ruins of the avant-garde, Millner-Larsen makes a critical intervention in our understanding of political art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aAnarchism and artzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aAnarchist artistszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aArt and social actionzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 7aART / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831107973290 cprintz978022682068240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226820699423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226820699/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles